The form ‘bardaicus' is not certain. Some MSS. have ‘ bardiacus ' which seems more suited to the metre. I doubt whether the second syllable of ‘ bardaicus ' according to its received etymology can be shortened. For this reason the reading ‘Archaicis' has been properly rejected in Horace, Epp. i. 5. 1, “ Si potes Archiacis conviva recum· bere lectis.'’ The name is said to be de- rived from the Bar-daei, an Illyrian peo- ple. from whom this sort of military shoe was taken, as it is said.

Juvenal says (according to the above) if a man wishes to punish the soldier who has maltreated him, the judex assigned to him is a ‘ bardaicus,' a great boot, and a pair of thick calves under a big bench: that is, he must carry his case into the camp, and if he is allowed a trial it will be a. court-mar- tial with a centurion for judex. ‘J udicem dare ' was properly said of the praetor who could appoint if he pleased a judex privatus to hear a private case at the instance of the
